rom three frontal cameras, and other nine continuous inputs representing the velocity, the next point from the sparse trajectory and a high-level driving command. We show that both of them are capable of imitating the expert trajectory from start to end after training ends, but the GAIL loss function that is augmented with BC outperforms the former in terms of convergence time and training stability.\nCandidate Topics: end to end principle, deep learning, generative grammar, stability, machine learning, supervised learning, artificial intelligence, artificial neural network, network architecture, process, correctness, reinforcement learning, adversarial system, unsupervised learning, recurrent neural network, scheme, convolutional neural network, construct, cloning, end user, adversarial machine learning, state, generative model, routing, convergence, upstream, control, semi supervised learning, parsing, robustness, protocol, modular design, domain, code, robot, network security, grammar induction, reliability, transduction, simple, online machine learning, process architecture, hidden markov model, regret, feedforward neural network, front and back ends, early stopping, downstream, transfer of learning, robot end effector, variety, server, schedule, task, top down and bottom up design, network planning and design, computer security, stochastic gradient descent, backbone network, throughput, image, end to end delay, segmentation, robot learning, markov chain, downstream, contextual image classification, feature learning, categorization, human computer interaction, gradient descent, packet loss, robotics, feature, robot kinematics, distributed computing, stochastic neural network, key, image segmentation, sequence learning, statistical classification, structured prediction, cascading style sheets, mechanism, benchmark, self organizing map, proactive learning, network performance, set, visualization, network complexity, face, network topology, iterative and incrementa